1
00:00:14,833 --> 00:00:15,833
They brought me here in an
H1 vehicle

2
00:00:17,166 --> 00:00:17,916
A closed one

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:20,500
Blindfolded the entire way

4
00:00:22,875 --> 00:00:24,708
They dropped us off at Bourj [Tower] Prison

5
00:00:25,416 --> 00:00:29,375
The road leading to the prison
was paved with gravel, not cement

6
00:00:30,125 --> 00:00:30,958
They brought us down

7
00:00:31,416 --> 00:00:35,333
Even the ones waiting for
us knew me by name

8
00:00:35,708 --> 00:00:39,125
Interviewer: Describe in detail
how you were taken to the prison

9
00:00:39,166 --> 00:00:39,833
We entered

10
00:00:40,166 --> 00:00:42,666
The entrance was gravel, they
dropped us off from the car here

11
00:00:43,791 --> 00:00:47,375
There was a small door
within the main gate

12
00:00:47,833 --> 00:00:51,541
He opened the small door and said, lift your feet
so we could enter. We were blindfolded of course

13
00:00:52,333 --> 00:00:53,208
We went inside

14
00:00:53,541 --> 00:00:57,000
We walked about ten steps

15
00:00:57,750 --> 00:01:00,000
They ordered us to face the wall
and left us like that for about an hour

16
00:01:00,833 --> 00:01:03,291
We stood facing this wall
for about an hour

17
00:01:03,375 --> 00:01:05,000
Then they continued
with us further inside

18
00:01:05,875 --> 00:01:07,375
They brought us in
through a small door here

19
00:01:09,416 --> 00:01:10,416
A small door

20
00:01:11,916 --> 00:01:13,041
They brought us inside

21
00:01:13,541 --> 00:01:14,833
Again we stood facing the wall

22
00:01:17,875 --> 00:01:20,291
Again we stayed for half
an hour or more

23
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:24,166
Here, through this door

24
00:01:26,958 --> 00:01:27,750
We entered here

25
00:01:29,541 --> 00:01:33,166
They stopped us in the middle of the room then
made us spin around to disorient us

26
00:01:33,666 --> 00:01:34,666
Then they stood us
facing the wall

27
00:01:35,500 --> 00:01:37,000
Of course no one knew
which direction they faced

28
00:01:37,208 --> 00:01:38,375
We stood here at this wall

29
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:40,625
We stood here for half an hour

30
00:01:40,708 --> 00:01:42,458
After that they started
taking us one by one

31
00:01:42,541 --> 00:01:47,208
To the interrogation room to
take our full information

32
00:01:47,541 --> 00:01:52,000
To get the name and create a file,
all of it was done using a laptop

33
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,958
After that I was transferred
to a solitary cell

34
00:02:02,416 --> 00:02:08,125
The solitary cell fits two mattresses
here and two mattresses there

35
00:02:08,458 --> 00:02:09,875
Meaning it fits
only four mattresses

36
00:02:11,208 --> 00:02:15,458
The most we reached in
the solitary cell was eight people

37
00:02:16,208 --> 00:02:17,416
We started sleeping sideways

38
00:02:18,166 --> 00:02:22,583
We pulled the mattresses toward the door where there was a space of about
one tile (40 cm), pulled the mattress and laid a blanket over it

39
00:02:23,833 --> 00:02:24,833
And it became enough
for eight people to sleep on

40
00:02:25,375 --> 00:02:28,791
Of course we slept, if you will
pardon me, like dogs inside it

41
00:02:29,833 --> 00:02:30,833
And the toilet is over there

42
00:02:32,125 --> 00:02:37,250
Its width is roughly two mattresses wide,
between one meter and a meter and a half

43
00:02:37,666 --> 00:02:38,250
No more

44
00:02:39,625 --> 00:02:44,916
Interviewer: Did you hear the names or noms de
guerre of the jailers you saw in the prison?

45
00:02:45,333 --> 00:02:47,083
The interrogator's name
was Abu al-Baraa

46
00:02:48,208 --> 00:02:51,541
He had green eyes and a
stocky build, decent looking

47
00:02:52,375 --> 00:02:54,958
And there was also Abu Sulaiman,
he used to come to our door

48
00:02:55,375 --> 00:02:58,083
This man was vile

49
00:02:59,583 --> 00:03:04,583
He only ever called us pig
and similar insults

50
00:03:05,375 --> 00:03:09,375
I will cut you to pieces,
and you I will throw over there

51
00:03:09,791 --> 00:03:11,250
That was Abu Sulaiman, a tall man

52
00:03:13,583 --> 00:03:19,250
And there was also a young man named Khaled,
known as Abu al-Walid, whose foot was amputated

53
00:03:20,083 --> 00:03:22,708
A respectful young man, fifteen
or sixteen years old

54
00:03:23,416 --> 00:03:26,750
His foot was amputated. He was also a jailer but he
came to the door with complete respect

55
00:03:27,125 --> 00:03:30,916
Abu Sulaiman was filthy and Abu
al-Baraa had absolutely no fear of God

56
00:03:32,875 --> 00:03:36,666
Interviewer: What was the charge they
brought against you to put you in prison?

57
00:03:36,791 --> 00:03:39,375
At the start of the interrogation
they accused me of espionage

58
00:03:39,791 --> 00:03:41,666
They were looking for
a phone on me

59
00:03:42,416 --> 00:03:48,083
I told them, you opened internet cafes and the
shop owner registers names

60
00:03:49,041 --> 00:03:52,208
In our neighborhood there was an
internet cafe owned by a man named Fahd

61
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,083
Of course he was
an informant for them

62
00:03:55,500 --> 00:03:56,625
And now he has fled

63
00:03:57,500 --> 00:04:02,791
I told him, this is my phone, I smashed it
in front of him and said take it and hand it to them

64
00:04:03,916 --> 00:04:06,875
From the start of the name registration, I smashed
my phone and gave it to him

65
00:04:07,416 --> 00:04:09,333
I did that so no one
would come after me

66
00:04:10,083 --> 00:04:13,708
You can control yourself from the inside but you
cannot control those on the outside from crossing lines

67
00:04:14,083 --> 00:04:14,541
Right?

68
00:04:15,083 --> 00:04:17,041
Many people were killed
because of a phone

69
00:04:17,083 --> 00:04:21,166
Because of blasphemy, people imprisoned with us received messages
containing blasphemy and they were told, you are accountable for it

70
00:04:22,416 --> 00:04:24,333
Of course in this case
there is personal enmity

71
00:04:26,666 --> 00:04:33,791
Interviewer: What dominated this place?
What did you feel while in this place?

72
00:04:34,041 --> 00:04:35,791
Of course fear
was always present

73
00:04:36,833 --> 00:04:42,208
The fear was not of dying in an airstrike but
of being killed

74
00:04:43,041 --> 00:04:45,416
When interrogation summons began,
everyone fell silent

75
00:04:47,458 --> 00:04:48,625
Everyone listened to what happened
in the interrogation room

76
00:04:48,666 --> 00:04:50,458
Beatings to the head,
breaking of hands

77
00:04:51,083 --> 00:04:53,416
And lifting us and slamming us
against the walls, that was the torture

78
00:04:53,708 --> 00:04:56,208
Interviewer: Tell us about the
torture methods you experienced

79
00:04:56,916 --> 00:04:59,583
Torture methods, I told you about
when I first entered

80
00:05:01,250 --> 00:05:02,666
The first five days
I was still conscious

81
00:05:03,500 --> 00:05:04,500
After that

82
00:05:05,833 --> 00:05:08,333
He hit me with a tile hammer

83
00:05:09,041 --> 00:05:13,083
It was white with a short green handle

84
00:05:13,208 --> 00:05:15,750
Because he showed it to me and said,
I will make this eat from your skull

85
00:05:17,250 --> 00:05:19,541
And indeed he did, this is the
mark of a blow on my head

86
00:05:20,250 --> 00:05:23,708
And here is something like
a fracture in my skull

87
00:05:24,333 --> 00:05:27,791
I remained unconscious for fifteen
to seventeen days, not knowing where I was

88
00:05:27,875 --> 00:05:30,416
When I regained consciousness I felt like I had
slept the night before and woken up today

89
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:32,708
That was all I knew

90
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:35,666
Interrogation started at 12:05
and went until 3 in the afternoon

91
00:05:36,208 --> 00:05:38,291
Sometimes until 2:30,
sometimes until 3:30

92
00:05:39,458 --> 00:05:41,125
That was the interrogation
schedule of course

93
00:05:42,041 --> 00:05:46,458
It was not ordinary beating, he was
hitting me with the hammer on my head

94
00:05:47,500 --> 00:05:50,166
Meaning, do not hide anything

95
00:05:50,166 --> 00:05:52,166
You know how
interrogation works

96
00:05:52,666 --> 00:05:57,083
For example he asks you, how many times
did you travel outside ISIS territory

97
00:05:57,166 --> 00:06:02,541
And you had answered twice,
once for work and once to visit

98
00:06:02,875 --> 00:06:05,750
Then he says, you traveled twice,
and hits you on the head

99
00:06:07,291 --> 00:06:11,708
He does not give you room to make
a mistake with any information

100
00:06:12,750 --> 00:06:17,708
Of course from the start of the interrogation he
records you on the laptop with audio and video

101
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:24,500
He talks to you with headphones on,
listening to your previous recordings and comparing

102
00:06:24,958 --> 00:06:29,083
Even if you spoke one word and there was a difference in dialect
between the rural Jazira dialect and the urban city dialect

103
00:06:29,083 --> 00:06:30,916
He would beat
you for it

104
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:33,500
He demands you speak
as you spoke before

105
00:06:35,708 --> 00:06:39,541
I endured a month of the
same daily interrogation

106
00:06:39,958 --> 00:06:41,750
Perhaps only one day a week
passed without interrogation

107
00:06:43,125 --> 00:06:44,833
But most of the month
they interrogated me

108
00:06:45,291 --> 00:06:47,333
Of course there was no one left in the town
of Tabqa the interrogator did not ask me about

109
00:06:48,916 --> 00:06:52,666
Of course most of his questions
were about people close to me

110
00:06:54,208 --> 00:06:59,750
What is your job? What do you do at night? Do you sleep
or go to work? Where do you go?

111
00:07:00,375 --> 00:07:02,333
Of course they were
afraid of assassinations

112
00:07:02,375 --> 00:07:06,791
And anyone who had been with the
Free Syrian Army, they were wary of

113
00:07:07,416 --> 00:07:12,083
Especially if they had not undergone
repentance, they remained under surveillance

114
00:07:13,875 --> 00:07:17,083
Of course when they
came to my house

115
00:07:17,166 --> 00:07:20,208
They sent a young man who was
one of my friends ahead of them

116
00:07:20,666 --> 00:07:22,416
To make sure I was home,
then they came after him

117
00:07:23,666 --> 00:07:24,958
Only two people came for me

118
00:07:25,666 --> 00:07:29,416
In an H1 vehicle. One of them told me, Abu Muhammad al-Amni
wants you to come answer a few questions

119
00:07:31,083 --> 00:07:34,083
From the moment I got in the car he treated me respectfully,
he said here is your blindfold, cover your head

120
00:07:34,458 --> 00:07:38,083
Interviewer: During the interrogation,
did you know they were recording you?

121
00:07:38,583 --> 00:07:40,875
Yes, I could hear
the laptop sound

122
00:07:42,833 --> 00:07:49,541
When he talked to me he said, I will ask
you a question and you must answer

123
00:07:50,208 --> 00:07:59,166
For example he asks me, what is your name? I say Humaidi,
he says wait and starts typing on the laptop

124
00:07:59,791 --> 00:08:05,375
Of course how did I know they were recording me even though I was blindfolded
and handcuffed behind my back, kneeling

125
00:08:05,916 --> 00:08:09,166
He told his assistant, point the camera
at him properly, he did not appear well

126
00:08:09,625 --> 00:08:11,166
That is how I knew
I was being filmed

127
00:08:11,708 --> 00:08:16,250
The second time they interrogated me he said, you know you were filmed
yesterday so do not make any mistakes with the information

128
00:08:17,041 --> 00:08:22,583
I told him, whoever does something
does not make mistakes in it

129
00:08:23,708 --> 00:08:29,166
More than once he asked me questions
that had nothing to do with them

130
00:08:29,583 --> 00:08:32,166
Two people interrogated me
whose names I do not know

131
00:08:32,625 --> 00:08:36,250
And a person named Abu al-Baraa whose role was
to finalize the information in the interrogation

132
00:08:37,333 --> 00:08:43,583
He was like the prison director, he personally
verified the interrogation with you

133
00:08:44,458 --> 00:08:49,000
In case you wanted to add information,
he would relay it to the previous interrogators

134
00:08:49,583 --> 00:08:54,041
One of the interrogators whose name was mentioned
in front of me was Abu Ubada

135
00:08:55,125 --> 00:08:59,416
At the start of my interrogation one of the members
mentioned his name and he said, shush, be quiet

136
00:09:00,333 --> 00:09:07,041
Interviewer: Did something happen to you in prison that you
still remember, something stuck in your memory since that day?

137
00:09:07,583 --> 00:09:09,750
All of my days with them
are unforgettable

138
00:09:12,375 --> 00:09:17,083
You live your life here in constant terror, you cannot see
anyone, you cannot even see their faces

139
00:09:17,583 --> 00:09:22,166
And your friends imprisoned with you, when one returns from the
interrogation room they would have told him, we will kill you

140
00:09:22,541 --> 00:09:24,250
It was impossible to hear
any good news

141
00:09:24,833 --> 00:09:28,625
Even your family does not know where you are
and there is no one to deliver news about you

142
00:09:30,208 --> 00:09:37,375
The interrogators I went to, no one came out from them alive. Most of
those they interrogated were executed

143
00:09:38,666 --> 00:09:43,583
Most of them were killed. Eventually only five of us from
the town of Tabqa remained and they took us

144
00:09:44,291 --> 00:09:50,166
Among them was a young man named Idris, a Kurdish man
they arrested because of his son's birthday party

145
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:54,041
He remained imprisoned
for about four months

146
00:09:54,541 --> 00:09:57,708
And also Shakir, they arrested
him and his wife

147
00:09:59,208 --> 00:10:06,083
And there were also Kurdish
young men whose names I forgot

148
00:10:06,791 --> 00:10:10,750
Over the passing days
I forgot their names

149
00:10:11,958 --> 00:10:16,500
And with us was also
Abboud al-Shawakh

150
00:10:17,291 --> 00:10:18,958
They used to suspend
him from the door

151
00:10:19,791 --> 00:10:22,250
This entire door was used
for <i>shabeh</i> [suspension]

152
00:10:23,666 --> 00:10:28,750
Of course in this corridor you hear nothing
but the sound of torture, God protect us

153
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:34,125
Women crying and men crying, women being
dragged on the ground and men being dragged

154
00:10:34,708 --> 00:10:35,375
Here of course

155
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,875
Of course they bring prisoners, we hear their
screaming but we cannot see them

156
00:10:43,416 --> 00:10:49,333
They brought us from the group cells,
we were in the group cell

157
00:10:50,541 --> 00:10:54,791
In the last group cell over there,
the one we were standing at

158
00:10:55,041 --> 00:10:56,916
They took us from there
and brought us in here

159
00:10:56,958 --> 00:10:58,166
There was a wall here

160
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,500
A black door, yes it was black

161
00:11:04,125 --> 00:11:05,708
We enter through this corridor

162
00:11:07,041 --> 00:11:08,166
This is the corridor for
the disciplinary cells

163
00:11:08,541 --> 00:11:10,416
Of course it fits
half a mattress

164
00:11:11,791 --> 00:11:14,083
Meaning half or three-quarters
of a mattress, no more

165
00:11:15,625 --> 00:11:16,708
Full of water

166
00:11:18,458 --> 00:11:22,750
Some prisoners here urinated
on themselves in the same spot

167
00:11:23,041 --> 00:11:25,916
Interviewer: Did you see anyone in
the disciplinary cells during cleaning?

168
00:11:25,958 --> 00:11:28,458
Yes, we saw one person and
he was one of our friends

169
00:11:28,500 --> 00:11:36,458
We came to clean the disciplinary cells
to bring our friend back to the group cell

170
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:39,500
We told them we wanted them to bring our
friend, we had requested him back

171
00:11:39,625 --> 00:11:41,875
He was an older man who did
not have the ability to endure

172
00:11:42,166 --> 00:11:44,208
They asked who would clean,
and I said I would clean

173
00:11:45,208 --> 00:11:46,875
We cleaned him up
and brought him out

174
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,625
Interviewer: What was
this person's name?

175
00:11:48,666 --> 00:11:49,875
The person's name was

176
00:11:54,291 --> 00:11:56,291
I do not know if he
is alive or dead

177
00:11:57,833 --> 00:12:00,333
I think his name was
Nasser or Sulaiman

178
00:12:00,708 --> 00:12:03,416
We went through many names in prison,
we no longer remember most of them

179
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:07,750
This was a long time ago, more than six
or seven years have passed, we no longer remember

180
00:12:13,333 --> 00:12:17,250
I saw many people from inside the
town of Tabqa and from outside it

181
00:12:17,791 --> 00:12:19,458
Like Sheikh Hassan al-Sannaa

182
00:12:20,166 --> 00:12:26,833
And also Kurdish young men, Idris,
Shakir, and Mustafa

183
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:33,500
Of course there were many people including Abdullah al-Rajab,
he was killed downstairs in the solitary cell

184
00:12:34,791 --> 00:12:38,083
They shot him on the day
of the airstrike on Bourj Prison

185
00:12:39,208 --> 00:12:42,583
During the first strike, he even took me
to him and said, is this not your friend?

186
00:12:44,208 --> 00:12:44,750
He took me

187
00:12:44,916 --> 00:12:48,125
He told me, lift your blindfold.
There was a curtain behind the door

188
00:12:48,833 --> 00:12:52,500
He directed me like this and said, lift your
blindfold and look at the door

189
00:12:52,541 --> 00:12:54,416
He opened the door and told
him to face the wall

190
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,958
He faced the wall, raised his hands,
then they shot him three times with a rifle

191
00:13:00,416 --> 00:13:02,375
And he told me, so you can
see that your fate is like this

192
00:13:03,750 --> 00:13:05,250
Then he took me
to the group cell

193
00:13:05,708 --> 00:13:08,291
Of course this is the group
cell I was in

194
00:13:10,791 --> 00:13:15,458
Interviewer: Were you able to communicate with anyone
in the other solitary cells? Could you hear anyone?

195
00:13:15,708 --> 00:13:19,666
I was here, next to me was
a cell for women

196
00:13:20,625 --> 00:13:23,625
The women would call to us,
there was a water hose between us

197
00:13:24,708 --> 00:13:28,833
The wall was not fully cemented, we could not
see through but we could hear

198
00:13:29,333 --> 00:13:34,333
The women spoke to us in whispers, saying if you get out
tell them I am imprisoned in this place

199
00:13:35,250 --> 00:13:37,416
If you get out, tell my family
or anyone about me

200
00:13:37,458 --> 00:13:40,416
Interviewer: Do you remember their names
or the charges against them?

201
00:13:40,416 --> 00:13:44,708
I remember one named Warda
and another named Samah

202
00:13:46,291 --> 00:13:47,291
Fatima

203
00:13:48,375 --> 00:13:49,916
These three women
are the ones I spoke with

204
00:13:50,541 --> 00:13:52,250
Interviewer: What were
the charges against them?

205
00:13:52,291 --> 00:13:55,791
One of them was charged with
photographing ISIS headquarters

206
00:13:57,250 --> 00:14:02,333
They confirmed it through her phone,
they found the evidence against her

207
00:14:02,375 --> 00:14:08,666
Of course she was executed
at a well by the river

208
00:14:09,416 --> 00:14:10,416
Designated only for women

209
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:16,250
Of course the torture of women
was beyond description

210
00:14:16,291 --> 00:14:17,375
The screaming of women

211
00:14:17,916 --> 00:14:21,791
Interrogation of women was from
4 AM until 6 AM

212
00:14:22,416 --> 00:14:23,541
This time was
designated for women only

213
00:14:24,250 --> 00:14:27,458
From 4 AM until 5 or 6 AM
was the women's interrogation

214
00:14:27,625 --> 00:14:30,916
Of course people could not
sleep from the fear

215
00:14:31,416 --> 00:14:37,583
Also on the topic, Mondays and Thursdays
were distinguished by severe torture

216
00:14:38,083 --> 00:14:40,458
The food on those days was rich
and the torture was harsh

217
00:14:40,875 --> 00:14:42,666
Even those taken for interrogation were
brought back carried in a blanket

218
00:14:43,583 --> 00:14:45,541
And there are people who
died under torture

219
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,875
One of them was a young man named
Khalaf from the village of Salhabiya

220
00:14:49,875 --> 00:14:52,291
They took him to the corridor
and executed him there

221
00:14:54,041 --> 00:14:55,125
He was executed
in the corridor

222
00:14:57,625 --> 00:15:03,333
Interviewer: You mentioned women were in the solitary cell next
to you. Were there women working as jailers?

223
00:15:03,375 --> 00:15:04,208
No

224
00:15:04,375 --> 00:15:07,750
Interviewer: How were
the women treated?

225
00:15:07,833 --> 00:15:10,583
The jailer would lead the
woman with a stick in his hand

226
00:15:11,333 --> 00:15:13,875
He would slide the blindfold under
the door for her to cover her eyes

227
00:15:14,291 --> 00:15:17,333
He opens the door and makes her hold the stick
and tells her to keep holding it, then leads her

228
00:15:17,708 --> 00:15:20,500
We would hear him say, keep holding
the stick and lift your foot

229
00:15:21,125 --> 00:15:22,750
Through this door, go inside

230
00:15:23,458 --> 00:15:29,791
We would hear the sound of their heads being struck with
<i>Lakhdar Brahimi</i>, a hose used for torture

231
00:15:30,708 --> 00:15:33,750
Of course we could hear
the sound of the blow to the head

232
00:15:33,875 --> 00:15:37,208
They only struck the head, a woman
was only struck on her head

233
00:15:42,333 --> 00:15:45,875
As for the food,
they served good food

234
00:15:46,708 --> 00:15:49,250
There were breakfast,
lunch, and dinner meals

235
00:15:50,166 --> 00:15:51,791
They served clean food

236
00:15:52,875 --> 00:15:55,291
I swear to God
their food was clean

237
00:15:57,583 --> 00:16:00,458
As a prisoner you never
lacked food

238
00:16:01,250 --> 00:16:03,083
Whenever you knocked on the door asking
for food they brought it at any time

239
00:16:04,083 --> 00:16:06,375
If you suddenly felt
hungry at night

240
00:16:06,416 --> 00:16:10,583
You know, we were smokers and we entered prison and quit smoking,
so our appetite for food increased greatly

241
00:16:11,958 --> 00:16:15,208
As for food, they served
plenty of it

242
00:16:16,791 --> 00:16:19,833
Interviewer: What were the meals
they used to distribute to you?

243
00:16:21,083 --> 00:16:30,375
They served breakfast in the morning with foul, msabbaha,
falafel, and sometimes maamouniya with cheese

244
00:16:32,291 --> 00:16:33,541
That was breakfast

245
00:16:33,666 --> 00:16:36,458
As for lunch, all the
meals were cooked

246
00:16:36,791 --> 00:16:37,541
All of them had meat

247
00:16:38,750 --> 00:16:40,041
Either chicken meat or lamb

248
00:16:41,375 --> 00:16:44,041
Interviewer: Was there a special day
or special meals?

249
00:16:44,125 --> 00:16:45,416
There were Mondays and Thursdays

250
00:16:46,166 --> 00:16:47,541
Some prisoners fasted on those days

251
00:16:48,458 --> 00:16:50,000
Inside the prison some
prisoners fasted

252
00:16:50,416 --> 00:16:51,291
Monday

253
00:16:52,375 --> 00:16:54,166
On Monday they served stuffed vegetables,
eggplant and zucchini stuffed with rice and meat

254
00:16:55,541 --> 00:16:56,541
Or <i>maqluba</i>
[upside-down rice dish]

255
00:16:58,416 --> 00:17:03,291
And on Thursday they served mandi plus cola,
of course with lamb

256
00:17:04,291 --> 00:17:06,916
These were special days when some prisoners
fasted on Mondays and Thursdays

257
00:17:08,125 --> 00:17:09,250
So they would separate
the fasting prisoners

258
00:17:09,375 --> 00:17:12,416
They honored those fasting with food,
and also honored them during interrogation

259
00:17:13,083 --> 00:17:15,000
Even when they took them for interrogation
they brought them back carried in a blanket

260
00:17:15,791 --> 00:17:21,791
Interviewer: Did you witness sick cases in the prison?
Did you see a sick person or did you get sick yourself?

261
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:26,208
As for illness

262
00:17:26,875 --> 00:17:28,541
They did not ignore any illness

263
00:17:28,583 --> 00:17:30,291
Whenever you knocked on the door
and told them you were sick

264
00:17:30,750 --> 00:17:34,875
They brought medicine to your cell. If you did
not improve, they took you to the hospital

265
00:17:35,875 --> 00:17:38,791
And if you needed to stay in the hospital,
they allowed that

266
00:17:39,375 --> 00:17:41,000
But the jailer is with you

267
00:17:41,041 --> 00:17:44,916
The blindfold must not be removed from your
head even when you are sick

268
00:17:46,250 --> 00:17:47,375
Then they return you to
the place you were imprisoned

269
00:17:49,541 --> 00:17:52,791
I am one of the people who
fell sick inside the prison

270
00:17:53,208 --> 00:17:55,541
I asked them to bring medicine and
they brought me the best medicine

271
00:17:57,791 --> 00:18:01,583
They brought me injections and continued
treating me for two months

272
00:18:03,291 --> 00:18:08,375
Due to the dampness and
our lack of sun exposure

273
00:18:08,916 --> 00:18:10,083
Our bodies changed

274
00:18:10,791 --> 00:18:13,833
As a result I developed
a severe allergic reaction

275
00:18:14,083 --> 00:18:15,416
Yet they did not abandon us

276
00:18:16,541 --> 00:18:19,083
Interviewer: How were the
bathroom conditions?

277
00:18:19,708 --> 00:18:20,833
As for the bathroom

278
00:18:21,541 --> 00:18:25,708
Of course hygiene inside the cell is not their concern,
it is your responsibility

279
00:18:25,750 --> 00:18:27,750
They give you all types
of cleaning supplies

280
00:18:28,625 --> 00:18:33,375
Like <i>ludaelin</i> [dish soap], giant brand, and Tai brand
cleaning powders, placed at the front of the bathroom

281
00:18:33,583 --> 00:18:38,875
Divided by a cinder block wall
with a military blanket as a door

282
00:18:43,916 --> 00:18:47,375
I was sentenced to execution
twice in this place

283
00:18:48,458 --> 00:18:50,250
The first time he told me,
your sentence is slaughter

284
00:18:51,083 --> 00:18:54,625
Of course I did not see a sharia judge.
The sentence is not pronounced like this

285
00:18:54,625 --> 00:18:59,291
From our time here we learned that the
sentence is pronounced in front of you

286
00:19:00,083 --> 00:19:03,208
The first time I was sentenced to slaughter, they dressed
me in an orange jumpsuit in the morning

287
00:19:04,125 --> 00:19:05,833
They took me to the corridor
and brought me back

288
00:19:06,250 --> 00:19:10,000
They told me, go take off the jumpsuit,
your sentence has been changed

289
00:19:10,750 --> 00:19:13,750
He said these words, brought me back,
I took off the jumpsuit and gave it to him

290
00:19:14,583 --> 00:19:16,708
In that moment the blood
froze in my veins

291
00:19:17,958 --> 00:19:20,458
The second time, seven
or eight days later

292
00:19:20,875 --> 00:19:26,291
Whoever entered my cell was not one of the
regular jailers, it was his first time coming to us

293
00:19:26,625 --> 00:19:28,833
He told me, take this, your jumpsuit,
get yourself ready

294
00:19:29,291 --> 00:19:34,625
Read the Quran, pray, and make your supplications.
Tomorrow morning you will be shot in public

295
00:19:35,375 --> 00:19:40,750
At the Shasha roundabout,
as they used to call it

296
00:19:43,125 --> 00:19:46,625
Of course in that moment all you
can say is God is sufficient for me

297
00:19:46,625 --> 00:19:49,458
You take the jumpsuit
without doing anything

298
00:19:49,708 --> 00:19:51,708
You take the jumpsuit and entrust
yourself to God, that is all

299
00:19:52,416 --> 00:19:55,916
Of course your fellow prisoners
gather around you for comfort

300
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:58,166
The next day they came
and took me

301
00:19:59,250 --> 00:20:02,625
They led me to the outer door
then brought me back

302
00:20:03,833 --> 00:20:07,708
He told his fellow jailer that the sharia
judge had called them

303
00:20:08,375 --> 00:20:14,166
And requested that no one be
executed until he arrives

304
00:20:15,916 --> 00:20:17,083
I heard these words myself

305
00:20:17,791 --> 00:20:20,208
That they would not execute anyone,
then they returned me to the group cell

306
00:20:21,083 --> 00:20:23,916
He said, God has saved you,
what is happening with you

307
00:20:23,958 --> 00:20:25,083
I told him I do not know

308
00:20:25,458 --> 00:20:27,916
Perhaps I am innocent and God does
not want you to be the cause of my death

309
00:20:28,708 --> 00:20:29,541
Then he returned me

310
00:20:30,166 --> 00:20:34,666
After that I completed four months
and they sentenced me to repentance

311
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,583
Of course he told me that in five days
we will know when we are getting out

312
00:20:40,125 --> 00:20:41,791
They took us from
here to Raqqa

313
00:20:45,833 --> 00:20:52,041
Interviewer: When you finished the repentance,
did they give you anything in Raqqa to help with that?

314
00:20:52,083 --> 00:20:53,666
Tell us about how you
did the repentance

315
00:20:53,708 --> 00:20:55,750
I did the repentance,
I am an illiterate person

316
00:20:55,791 --> 00:21:00,500
So I spent six months with sheikhs
and memorized from them

317
00:21:01,791 --> 00:21:06,958
I memorized. The questions I could answer were questions that
literate people could not answer

318
00:21:07,333 --> 00:21:10,458
Among them two lawyers who did not
achieve the results I achieved

319
00:21:11,333 --> 00:21:16,541
Of course all prisoners study from books. I would listen to
what they read and review it once in my memory

320
00:21:17,875 --> 00:21:20,791
During the repentance they
gave me a non-harassment order

321
00:21:21,958 --> 00:21:26,208
They gave it to me because I saw one of their faces after
I removed the window to look at people

322
00:21:26,416 --> 00:21:27,500
I just wanted to
see human beings

323
00:21:27,833 --> 00:21:32,041
The repentance center was on the second floor,
the room door was not a prison door

324
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:35,333
The repentance room door was a wooden
door but the prison was below

325
00:21:36,041 --> 00:21:39,083
Interviewer: Do you remember anyone who
was with you during the repentance?

326
00:21:39,125 --> 00:21:44,500
During the repentance Idris was with me
and Kurdish young men

327
00:21:44,666 --> 00:21:48,791
The same Kurdish young men,
Shakir and Nazim

328
00:21:49,750 --> 00:21:52,791
These were the Kurdish young men who
were with me, and Mustafa as well

329
00:21:55,250 --> 00:22:00,625
There were also four or five young men with me but I no
longer remember their names, they were from the town of Tabqa

330
00:22:00,791 --> 00:22:05,958
There was also someone from the Junaidat family,
all of us did the repentance

331
00:22:06,666 --> 00:22:12,875
Even one of the young men with us in the repentance
named Idris committed blasphemy

332
00:22:13,708 --> 00:22:16,166
He was a Kurdish young man arrested
because he held a birthday party

333
00:22:16,416 --> 00:22:17,416
He committed blasphemy
outside of the repentance

334
00:22:18,416 --> 00:22:19,541
Who heard him?

335
00:22:20,416 --> 00:22:23,166
Me and the young man who had a dispute with him,
and the problem happened between them, also Kurdish

336
00:22:23,833 --> 00:22:28,375
I was the only one sitting with them. They were reading from
books and I was listening to them to memorize

337
00:22:29,916 --> 00:22:32,916
So the jailer called for me because
he did not trust the Kurdish young men

338
00:22:33,166 --> 00:22:34,916
He took me downstairs and made me
swear on the Holy Quran

339
00:22:38,291 --> 00:22:41,708
I pray to God to forgive me because by doing
so I did not cause harm to anyone

340
00:22:41,958 --> 00:22:43,458
And if I had testified otherwise
he would have been killed

341
00:22:43,791 --> 00:22:47,000
Because he had completed repentance
and then apostasized afterward, as they told me

342
00:22:47,250 --> 00:22:50,250
The sin falls upon you. Did
he commit blasphemy or not?

343
00:22:52,291 --> 00:22:56,125
He pressed me greatly,
his name was Abu Muhammad al-Amni

344
00:22:57,375 --> 00:23:03,000
Even when he saw that I had seen his face from the window
while he was getting into a white Kia car

345
00:23:04,375 --> 00:23:07,208
He looked at the window and saw me standing,
so I closed the window immediately

346
00:23:07,291 --> 00:23:11,125
He came upstairs masked, called
for me, and took me downstairs

347
00:23:11,625 --> 00:23:14,541
He allowed me to call my family for three
minutes on the landline phone

348
00:23:15,916 --> 00:23:18,500
He told me, I gave you this opportunity so you
do not tell anyone that you saw me

349
00:23:18,875 --> 00:23:20,625
He had a distinctive
birthmark on his face

350
00:23:22,708 --> 00:23:24,250
He was a person with clear
and distinctive features

351
00:23:24,750 --> 00:23:27,833
He was a good and respectful man,
he had no business with us

352
00:23:27,916 --> 00:23:30,208
I told you before, our room door was a
repentance door, not a prison door

353
00:23:30,416 --> 00:23:36,000
Sheikhs came to us daily to teach
us creed, jurisprudence, and Quran

354
00:23:36,458 --> 00:23:39,416
Those were the lessons they taught us. They also
encouraged us to watch the propaganda videos

355
00:23:39,416 --> 00:23:43,375
They took our friends who were with us in prison and
brought us their execution videos to watch

356
00:23:49,541 --> 00:24:02,708
This group cell faces the interrogation room and holds
prisoners who would stay for a long period

357
00:24:04,333 --> 00:24:09,791
They assigned them most tasks like
going to the kitchen and cleaning it

358
00:24:11,500 --> 00:24:21,208
With me was Abboud and some young men from city
neighborhoods, and some of them were killed

359
00:24:21,541 --> 00:24:27,875
There was Abu al-Nour from the town
of Tabqa, also among the imprisoned youth

360
00:24:29,333 --> 00:24:33,000
There are many names that were with us but I cannot
remember them. Idris was with us too, and Shakir

361
00:24:34,541 --> 00:24:37,666
Interviewer: What was the difference between
the group cell and the solitary cell?

362
00:24:37,791 --> 00:24:40,166
The solitary cell only fits four mattresses
while the group cell is very large

363
00:24:40,333 --> 00:24:43,291
The group cell is a room
but much larger in size

364
00:24:43,791 --> 00:24:46,875
The group cell is approximately eight
meters long and eight meters wide

365
00:24:47,208 --> 00:24:52,208
Of course there is no ventilation hole,
no exhaust fan, nothing at all

366
00:24:52,416 --> 00:24:55,458
There is a toilet and a
<i>qazan</i> [water heater]

367
00:24:56,208 --> 00:24:59,041
Interviewer: Did anyone among you
think about escaping this place?

368
00:24:59,083 --> 00:25:00,875
There was absolutely
no possibility of escape

369
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:04,666
Because when you look around you see
very thick iron bars

370
00:25:04,708 --> 00:25:12,291
You look at the window and find it sealed with cement,
you cannot even see daylight, only the lightbulb

371
00:25:13,208 --> 00:25:15,500
Interviewer: Was the light controlled
by them or by you?

372
00:25:15,541 --> 00:25:15,875
No

373
00:25:16,625 --> 00:25:21,541
Controlled by them, but they never turned it off
because of the cameras, they cannot monitor us without it

374
00:25:22,291 --> 00:25:26,416
Sometimes the generator broke down
for five minutes

375
00:25:27,333 --> 00:25:32,750
They would get anxious and fix it quickly,
it must not be off for more than ten minutes

376
00:25:32,833 --> 00:25:37,583
Interviewer: How did they react
when the prison was bombed?

377
00:25:37,625 --> 00:25:40,125
Of course we were prisoners in a basement,
we could not hear everything

378
00:25:40,208 --> 00:25:47,833
We heard a sound from above during the first strike. We were
hit by three missiles and felt the building shake

379
00:25:47,875 --> 00:25:51,500
But the sound was not too loud because the place
was fortified with sandbag barriers around it

380
00:25:51,625 --> 00:25:54,958
As is visible in
that group cell

381
00:25:55,833 --> 00:25:59,375
This group cell we lived in still
has the same bags to this day

382
00:26:00,916 --> 00:26:03,291
These very bags, sandbags

383
00:26:03,958 --> 00:26:06,250
As you can see, the thickness
of the concrete underneath

384
00:26:06,916 --> 00:26:09,083
You cannot even think of escaping
and we were in a basement

385
00:26:09,375 --> 00:26:11,166
There is no possibility
of digging to escape

386
00:26:12,333 --> 00:26:15,416
Besides that, there were cameras
one here and another there

387
00:26:16,625 --> 00:26:18,208
Interviewer: Did you write
a memory of yours here?

388
00:26:18,250 --> 00:26:20,791
I am an illiterate person,
I cannot read or write

389
00:26:22,125 --> 00:26:24,583
Interviewer: How did you
manage to get out of prison?

390
00:26:24,708 --> 00:26:27,208
I spent four months
in Bourj Prison

391
00:26:28,666 --> 00:26:36,166
The last strike on the prison was powerful. The next day
they gradually started transferring us to Raqqa prison

392
00:26:36,916 --> 00:26:42,000
They took three of us out of this place,
with us was an Iraqi young man

393
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:45,583
And a young man named Mustafa
from Tabqa

394
00:26:46,833 --> 00:26:54,791
We left here by car on the Jazira road, crossed the river
using barges that transport people and cars

395
00:26:55,875 --> 00:26:58,750
The van boarded the barge
and we crossed to the city of Raqqa

396
00:26:59,166 --> 00:27:00,708
At this point our sentence
had been handed down

397
00:27:01,916 --> 00:27:05,041
We went to do the repentance
but when, we did not know

398
00:27:05,375 --> 00:27:08,125
But after we arrived there

399
00:27:08,458 --> 00:27:13,458
The interrogator Abu al-Baraa entrusted
us to them as a safekeeping

400
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:16,541
He tells them, these are entrusted to you
because the repentance course was closed

401
00:27:17,416 --> 00:27:21,791
So when the current repentance course ends
they would include us in the new one

402
00:27:22,750 --> 00:27:27,083
They left us at Point 11, at the Black
Stadium, which is well known

403
00:27:28,708 --> 00:27:30,708
There is a room downstairs
that has mirrors

404
00:27:32,791 --> 00:27:34,458
That was all we knew

405
00:27:35,458 --> 00:27:41,333
I stayed there for a month and also
stayed a month for the repentance

406
00:27:44,083 --> 00:27:48,458
Here things got confused for me,
I was sentenced to execution

407
00:27:48,666 --> 00:27:51,541
And I saw judges who uncovered my
face and took me upstairs

408
00:27:52,916 --> 00:28:00,000
They asked me my name. I told them Humaidi, they
looked at the name they had and it was Hamid

409
00:28:00,958 --> 00:28:02,666
There had been a mix-up
in the names

410
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:09,166
Of course they removed my blindfold and I saw their faces because
I had been sentenced to execution by firing squad in public

411
00:28:10,625 --> 00:28:19,416
When they realized they had the wrong name they
threatened me not to tell anyone I saw their faces

412
00:28:19,791 --> 00:28:28,166
Then they returned me downstairs because I had dared to speak up. Since I was
going to die anyway, I told them how can you sentence me when I came as an entrusted person

413
00:28:29,791 --> 00:28:34,125
He asked me my name, and here they remembered to ask
my name. They even broke my ID card

414
00:28:34,625 --> 00:28:38,416
He broke my ID card
into four pieces, as you can see

415
00:28:40,708 --> 00:28:42,166
I started looking at my name

416
00:28:46,416 --> 00:28:47,250
This is my ID card

417
00:28:48,250 --> 00:28:50,791
He broke it into more
than three pieces

418
00:28:52,375 --> 00:28:55,041
He broke it from here and
split it lengthwise like this

419
00:28:56,041 --> 00:29:00,125
When he saw the name he said, this is not the
person wanted for execution

420
00:29:01,208 --> 00:29:08,791
Here they started warning me to pretend I saw nothing, and the last
thing they said was I would take this man's place if I said anything

421
00:29:09,416 --> 00:29:12,958
Interviewer: Was there a difference in treatment
between Bourj Prison and the Stadium Prison?

422
00:29:13,208 --> 00:29:21,416
Here at first the treatment was bad
until our sentence was handed down

423
00:29:21,625 --> 00:29:24,750
We did not know our sentence had been handed
down, but things started to improve

424
00:29:24,750 --> 00:29:29,166
We were placed in a group cell
and many things became available

425
00:29:29,833 --> 00:29:33,333
There we would get a cup
of tea with every meal

426
00:29:33,750 --> 00:29:37,875
Here there was a thermos for tea,
and you made your own coffee

427
00:29:38,458 --> 00:29:43,166
Anything you wanted, he would take you to the
kitchen to get whatever you needed

428
00:29:44,583 --> 00:29:49,250
Interviewer: What has changed about this place
between the past and the present?

429
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:53,083
The cinder blocks were removed, and the walls
dividing sections of the group cell were taken down

430
00:29:53,458 --> 00:29:56,375
The group cell was divided,
it reached up to here

431
00:29:57,583 --> 00:29:59,166
Its length went up
to this white paint mark

432
00:30:01,916 --> 00:30:03,541
Its bathroom was in the back

433
00:30:05,166 --> 00:30:06,875
The group cell bathroom was large

434
00:30:07,166 --> 00:30:08,041
And the solitary cells were here

435
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:15,791
Interviewer: Was the bathroom flooded? Were hot
and cold water available?

436
00:30:15,875 --> 00:30:19,333
As for the group cell bathroom,
the electrical switch is with you

437
00:30:21,208 --> 00:30:24,791
The switch in the group cell
you can flip it on and off

438
00:30:25,125 --> 00:30:28,375
In the solitary cells only
cold water was available

439
00:30:29,416 --> 00:30:33,625
Everyone shares one
water tank

440
00:30:34,791 --> 00:30:36,833
Meaning there is not enough
time for the water to heat up

441
00:30:39,541 --> 00:30:43,541
Interviewer: Could you shower whenever you wanted?
Did they bring you shampoo?

442
00:30:43,583 --> 00:30:44,583
However you wished

443
00:30:45,458 --> 00:30:49,000
As for hygiene, they encouraged it and
provided all cleaning supplies

444
00:30:49,458 --> 00:30:56,708
They provided shampoo and soap, whenever
you wanted these things they supplied them

445
00:30:57,875 --> 00:31:00,208
And the bathroom switch is with
you in the group cell

446
00:31:00,708 --> 00:31:02,375
And hygiene is your
responsibility

447
00:31:02,708 --> 00:31:04,208
Of course they do not like
to see the place dirty

448
00:31:05,291 --> 00:31:08,583
And a person in prison will not
dirty the place much

